{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","titleTextRelFontSize":10,"subTitleText":"","subTitleTextRelFontSize":6,"presenterText":"","presenterTextRelFontSize":4,"dateText":"","dateTextRelFontSize":3,"logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","sectionTextRelFontSize":8,"smallerSectionText":"","smallerSectionTextRelFontSize":5},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false,"span":3,"markdown":"ANC1 volumes fluctuated through 2025, reaching a low of ~180,000 in early 2025 and a high of over 240,000 in July 2025.

ANC4 showed stable but lower volumes, between ~55,000 and ~60,000 monthly visits since 2023. 

Addressing gaps between first and fourth visits remains critical to ensure continuity of care and improved antenatal outcomes."},{"type":"figure","presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"fd8865a2-ee71-4f48-8d92-1b95c355eade","moduleId":"m003","isDefault":false,"selectedReplicantValue":"anc_SM","replicateBy":"indicator_common_id"},"stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in antenatal care"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"ANC1 trends were more volatile, with several surpluses in 2023 followed by disruptions throughout 2024 and early 2025, averaging ~13% below expected levels during the disruption periods. In 2025, volumes alternated between peaks of surplus and valleys of disruption, converging by September 2025 when actual and expected volumes aligned.

ANC4 volumes closely tracked expected trends through 2023, before consistent disruptions across 2024 and 2025, averaging ~11% below expected levels in both years.

Far fewer women progress from ANC1 to ANC4, underscoring a persistent continuity gap in antenatal care."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"85fc6d89-048c-4ae0-83c0-5c2d6f951db0","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"anc_SM","isDefault":false,"replicateBy":"indicator_common_id"}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"ANC service shows disruption in 2024 and 2025, with more volatility in disruptions and surpluses in ANC1"}}

